Introduction to the Dataset:

  • This dataset consists of reviews from amazon on different products over the span of a 18 year period up to March 2013.
  • This dataset is a subset dataset consisting of a total of 1 800 000 records
  • The sentiment of each review has already been specified in the dataset
  • The sentiment for each review has been decided by taking the review score 1 and 2 as negative and 4 and 5 as positive
  • Review scores of 3 have been ignored to improve the models ability to distingush between positive and negative sentiment
    • In [ ]:
    # Import the raw dataset using Pandas and create a dataframe with specified column names
data = pd.read_csv('amazon_reviews.csv')

    The dataset consists of three columns:

  • Sentiment: 1 is negative and 2 is positive
  • Review Title: The review heading
  • Review text: The review body

    • Due to the large size of the dataset, I have decided to randomly select 540 000 observations and create a new csv file. The original dataset is on kaggle
    This decision is to reduce the run time of my model when testing and to satisfy the minimum record requirement for Task 1

    # Pipeline methods for cleaning the data and feature engineering

# Specified stop words to be removed from the data
# Certain words may change the meaning of the next word therefore the stop words are specified

stop_words= ['yourselves', 'between', 'whom', 'itself', 'is', "she's", 'up', 'herself', 'here', 'your', 'each', 
             'we', 'he', 'my', "you've", 'having', 'in', 'both', 'for', 'themselves', 'are', 'them', 'other',

# Function to remove null values
class ClearNulls(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        #drop missing reviews
        X = X.dropna()
        return X

# Function to combine review title and review text
class CombineReviewSum(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        # Combine the review_title and review_test 
        X['reviews'] = X['review_title'].str.cat(X['review_text'], sep=' ')
        
        return X.drop(['review_title', 'review_text'], axis=1)

# Function to remove punctuation
class RemovePunctuation(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        # remove punctuation
        def clean_review(text):
            text = str(text).lower()
            text = re.sub('\[.*?\]', '', text)
            text = re.sub('https?://\S+|www\.\S+', '', text)
            text = re.sub('<.*?>+', '', text)
            text = re.sub('[%s]' % re.escape(string.punctuation), '', text)
            text = re.sub('\n', '', text)
            text = re.sub('\w*\d\w*', '', text)
            return text
            
        X['reviews'] = X['reviews'].apply(lambda x: clean_review(x))
        return X

# Function to remove stop words
class StopWords (BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        # remove stop words
        X['reviews'] = X['reviews'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in x.split() if word not in (stop_words)]))
        return X

#Function to one-hot encode the data
class LabelEncoder(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        # label encode the sentiment column
        le = preprocessing.LabelEncoder() 
        X['sentiment']= le.fit_transform(X['sentiment']) 
        return X

    The pipleline used for cleaning performs the following tasks:

  • Removes all nulls
  • Combine review_title and review_text columns
  • Removes all punctuation
  • Removes specified stop_words
  • One-hot encodes sentiment column

    • Please Note:
    Due to the nature of the dataset being amazon reviews, it is important to include stop words like "not" because it can change the meaning or interpretation of the review.
    This is the reason for specifying what stop words must be removed from the text.

    During testing I created the model only using the review_text column, this resulted in an accuracy of 85%.
    To increase the models accuracy and perfomance, I have combined the review_title and review_text columns.
    This resulted in an increase of 7-8% in the models performance from 85% to 93%

    # Calls the pipeline methods
pipe = Pipeline([

    ('combinereviewsum', CombineReviewSum()),
    ('removepunctuation', RemovePunctuation()),
    ('stopword', StopWords()),
    ('labelencoder', LabelEncoder())
])

    • Lemmatization:¶

    In [ ]:
    # Applying Lemmmatizer to remove tenses from texts.
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

def preprocess_text(text):
    text = re.sub(r"won\'t", "will not", text)
    text = re.sub(r"can\'t", "can not", text)
    text = re.sub('[^a-zA-Z0-9]',' ',text)
    text = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in text.split() if not word in set(stop_words)]
    text = ' '.join(text)
    return text

    • N-Gram:¶

    From the WordCloud, we gain an understanding of what type of words are mainly used in each type of review.
    The issue is that certain words are common between both types of reviews like product or book.
    Therefore to gain a better visualization of the dataset, an N-Gram can be used to display common phrases used in the reviews.

    In [ ]:
    # allows plotyly graphs to be illustrated in the notebook
pio.renderers.default = "notebook_connected"
    In [ ]:
    ## custom function for ngram generation 
def generate_ngrams(text, n_gram = 1):
    token = [token for token in text.lower().split(" ") if token != "" if token not in stop_words]
    ngrams = zip(*[token[i:] for i in range(n_gram)])
    return [" ".join(ngram) for ngram in ngrams]
    In [ ]:
    # custom function for horizontal bar chart 
def horizontal_bar_chart(df, color):
    trace = go.Bar(
        y =df["word"].values[::-1],
        x = df["wordcount"].values[::-1],
        showlegend = False,
        orientation = 'h',
        marker = dict(
            color = color,
        ),
    )
    return trace

    In [ ]:
    # Splits the data into training and testing dataframes

    In [ ]:
    # Long Short Term Memory Neural Network
embed_dim = 128 # Hypertuned Embedding Dimension
lstm_out = 196 # Hypertuned LSTM Output Dimension

vocab_size = len(tokenizer.word_index) + 1

model = Sequential() # Initializes the model
model.add(Embedding(max_fatures,embed_dim,input_length = X.shape[1])) # Adds the embedding layer
model.add(SpatialDropout1D(0.4))# Adds the Spatial Dropout Layer
model.add(LSTM(lstm_out, dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0)) # Adds the LSTM Layer
model.add(Dense(2,activation='softmax')) # Adds the Dense Layer
model.compile(loss = 'sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam',metrics = ['accuracy']) # Compiles the model
print(model.summary()) # Prints the model summary

  • The model has been compiled using the sparse_categorical_crossentropy loss and activation function softmax.
  • These two methods are the most appropriate for the type of input data I am providing to the model.
  • The optimizer selected is adam and the metric is accuracy. These two methods provide the best accuracy for NLP data while still keeping the runtime manageable.
  • The tuned hyperparameters are: embed_dim = 128, lstm_out = 196 and dropout = 0.2
  • The max features has been specified to 2000 by the tokenizer, this will ensure that the model doesnt add unneccessary weighting to meaningless words

    ''' 
from tkinter import *
class App(object):
    def __init__(self, window):

        lbl = Label(
            window,
            text="Please Enter a Review below:",
            fg="black",
            font=("Arial", 16),
        )
        lbl.place(x=60, y=10)

        # Text box
        self.txtfld1 = Entry(window, bd = 5, font=("Arial", 8))
        self.txtfld1.place(x=75, y=50,height=60, width=250)

        # Button
        self.btn = Button(
            window, text="Predict", fg="green", command=self.MyButtonClicked
        )
        self.btn.place(x=180, y=120)

    def MyButtonClicked(self):
        user_sentiment = 0
        user_input_review_title = ""
        user_input_review_text = self.txtfld1.get() 

        # Add text to new dataframe
        user_input_df = pd.DataFrame({"sentiment":[user_sentiment],"review_title":[user_input_review_title],"review_text":[user_input_review_text]}) 

        # call cleaning pipeline
        user_input_cleaned_text = pipe.fit_transform(user_input_df)
        # Tokenizes the reviews, fits text and adds padding to the reviews 
        X2 = np.array(user_input_cleaned_text['reviews'])
        X2 = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X2)
        X2 = pad_sequences(X2, maxlen = 75)

        # Predicts the sentiment of the review and returns the predicted sentiment
        user_input_prediction = model.predict(X2)
        temp_result = np.argmax(user_input_prediction)

        print("Button clicked")
        print(temp_result)

        if (temp_result) == 0:
            print("This was a negative review")
            lbl = Label(
            window,
            text="This was a negative review",
            fg="black",
            font=("Arial", 12),
            )
            lbl.place(x=130, y=150)
        else:
            print("This was a positive review")
            lbl = Label(
            window,
            text="This was a positive review",
            fg="black",
            font=("Arial", 12),
            )
            lbl.place(x=130, y=150)
        
        
if __name__ == "__main__":
    window = Tk()
    app = App(window)
    window.title("Review Sentiment Prediction Application")
    window.geometry("400x200+600+150")
    mainloop()

    In [ ]:
    embed_dim1 = 96
lstm_out1 = 64

    Conclusion:¶

    After visualizing the dataset, it contained a balanced number of positive and negative reviews.
    The most common phrase used in the negative reviews was “don’t waste money” and the most common phrase used in the positive reviews was “highly recommend book”.
    Once the model was built using text data from Amazon reviews, it achieved an accuracy of 92% and a loss of 0.20.
    This model performed much better when compared to the test model (untuned hyperparameters) that had an accuracy of 84% and a loss of 0.36.
    The model that achieved an accuracy of 92% can be used to successfully identify sentiment within text and categorize whether the review is positive or negative.
